message: Ah, nice. I visited Stanford for a couple of weeks during my PhD, because I collaborated with one of the astrophysicist there. It’s a very nice campus, although I did find the atmosphere there very competitive. What was the topic of your thesis? Astrophysics to quant wasn’t as big a switch as one might imagine. Obviously a lot of finance knowledge to pick up, but a lot of the statistical and computational methods are very similar. I mostly focus on fixed income. What kind of work are you in now?
Can you tell me about the switch from astrophysicist to quant? What do you trade?

I would guess that you haven’t used them. I was the student PI on a university satellite in undergrad, then I worked on a satellite that blew up for a defunct company called planetary resources, then spent a year at planet labs building the worlds largest earth imaging constellation (several hundred satellites), and another university sat when I was a PhD student at Stanford. I didn’t go out of my way for the perseids this year, but will do something special (TBD) for the Geminid.

That’s pretty impressive. For which satellites? I’m wondering if I came across their data in my research. No, I didn’t actively go looking for the meteor shower, and I think it’s too bright to see them properly in the city :(. Did you do anything to see them?
Did you do anything for the perseids meteor shower?
Thank god. I’m a space enthusiast. I worked on 3 types of space telescopes  (4 generations of satellites in total) and used to help run a student space advocacy nonprofit called SEDS.
Phenomenological actually :). I guess that sort of qualifies as theoretical though. Are you an Astrophysics enthusiast?
